Vercel Web Analytics Installation and Configuration

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the Tailored project.

## Changes Made:

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` package (version determined by npm)
- Updated package.json dependencies
- Updated package-lock.json with new dependency tree

### 2. Code Configuration
Modified: frontend/src/app/layout.tsx
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component to the root layout body, alongside the existing `<SpeedInsights />` component

## Implementation Details:

Following the official Vercel Analytics quickstart documentation (fetched on 2026-03-25), I:
1. Identified this as a Next.js 16 project using the App Router pattern
2. Used npm (the project's package manager, as indicated by package-lock.json)
3. Added the Analytics component to the root layout at `src/app/layout.tsx`
4. Placed the component within the `<body>` tag alongside SpeedInsights and Toaster components

The implementation follows Next.js App Router best practices:
- Analytics component imported from '@vercel/analytics/next' (framework-specific import)
- Placed in the root layout to track all routes automatically
- No additional configuration needed - works out of the box

## Verification:

- ✅ Build completed successfully (npm run build)
- ✅ TypeScript compilation passed
- ✅ All static pages generated without errors
- ✅ No breaking changes introduced
- ℹ️ No linter or test scripts configured in this project

## Post-Deployment:

After deploying to Vercel, analytics will automatically begin collecting data. You can verify the setup by:
- Checking the browser's Network tab for requests to `/<unique-path>/view`
- Viewing analytics data in your Vercel dashboard

The Analytics component seamlessly integrates with Next.js routing and will track page views across all routes in the application.
